data.title: Samosir Island
data.description: The island of Samosir, situated in the huge crater lake of Toba. The island, together with its surrounding areas is the heart of the Toba Batak culture. A visit to Lake Toba is not complete without a stay on Samosir with its many traditional villages along its shoreline.

data.title: Sigale-gale Puppet Show
data.description: Sigale-gale is a Batak life-sized puppet show, which is traditionally performed at funerals but may now also be performed for visitors.

data.title: Oukup
data.description: The Batak ethnic groups living in North Sumatera have long realized that nature is not only man’s  main source of life but it also provides precious medicinal cures. Traditional natural treatments have long been part of daily life in North Sumatera.

data.title: Bukit Lawang
data.description: Bukit Lawang is a small village situated at the south of the Mount Leuseur National Park and the gateway to the legendary Sumatran jungle.

data.title: Tidung Island
data.description: Located relatively close to the capital city of Jakarta, you wouldn’t have to spend unnecessary time and money just trying to get to Tidung Island. For Jakarta-dwellers looking for a simple and affordable weekend getaway, Tidung offers secluded beaches, starry nights and an amiable community, just a stone’s throw away from the capital.

data.title: Bidadari Island
data.description: The island gained its name because long ago, no one was allowed to visit the island unless they were of royal blood of Jayakarta. Hence the name, Pulau Bidadari, literally translated meaning The Island of Angels. With only 6 hectares in area, Pulau Bidadari is a small island. You could walk from one end to the other in under two hours. The beaches of Pulau Bidadari display beautiful, white, sand, and crystal clear sea water.

data.title: Fatahilah Museum
data.description: Originally called the Stadhuis, this building was built in 1710 by Governor General van Riebeeck, this solid building hides below it notorious dungeons and filthy water prisons. Today, this museum displays the history of Jakarta from prehistoric days to the founding of the town of Jayakarta in 1527 by Prince Fatahillah of Banten, until Indonesia’s Independence in 1945.

data.title: National Museum
data.description: The National Museum is the pride of Jakarta, providing visitors an insight into Indonesia’s long history in cultural heritage from prehistoric days up to today. Having recently been expanded, the museum houses an impressive collection of no less than 109,342 objects covering Indonesia’s Prehistory, Archaeology, Ethnography, Numismatics-Heraldic, Geography and Historical Relics.

data.title: National Monument
data.description: The 137 meter tall National Monument is obelisk shaped, and is topped with a 14.5 meter bronze flame coated with 32 kilograms gold leaf. A lift takes visitors up to the look-out platform at the base of the flame for a grand view of Jakarta.

data.title: Jakarta Dining Experience
data.description: Everywhere around this city one finds simple restaurants and street stalls so that no one can ever complain of having to go hungry for lack of food available. Diners can pick from a wide selection of authentic Indonesian delicacies or international cuisine from Japanese sushi to juicy steaks, to crunchy salads.

data.title: Jakarta Street Food Scene
data.description: The local food scene relies heavily on street food, a quick meal sold by a vendor with a push cart, basket, at a stall, or possibly at a store where customers can see the preparation of food clearly. The types of food offered vary from a simple fried tofu to a much more complicated dish.

data.title: Jakarta Shopping Extravaganza
data.description: Jakarta has indeed everything and anything you might just be looking for. To Jakartans, shopping and spending the whole day in malls is entertainment. Jakarta malls offer everything from large department stores, luxury boutiques, supermarket, gym, upmarket restaurants, food centers, cafes, bookshops, kids playground, beauty salons, to cinemas, all under one roof and in total air-conditioned comfort.

data.title: Ancol
data.description: Jakarta's largest and most popular recreation park, Ancol Dreamland has an extensive range of attractions that include an oceanaquarium, a water park, Dufan Theme Park, art center, convention hall and hotels. Also you can buy Indonesian art as souvenir at Pasar Seni or Art Market.

data.title: Taman Mini Indonesia Indah
data.description: Taman Mini Indonesia Indah or Beautiful Indonesia in Miniature Park is an extensive culture-based park. Popularly known as Taman Mini, the core of the Park are 26 exclusive replicas of traditional houses of chieftains found throughout the Indonesian archipelago.

data.title: Prambanan
data.description: Located not far from the Buddhist Borobudur temple, Prambanan is the largest Hindu temple in Southeast Asia with magnificent spectacle and an icon of Indonesia’s cultural heritage.

data.title: Borobudur
data.description: Borobudur is the world’s biggest Buddhist monument and an ancient site widely considered to be one of the world’s seven wonders. Located on the island of Java, the temple sits majestically on a hilltop overlooking lush green fields and distant hills.

data.title: Yogya Dining Guide
data.description: Truly a unique city. Ruled by a king (sultan) whose lineage can be traced to centuries, this city offers plenty cultural and historical heritage and offers many luscious delicacies.

data.title: Malioboro
data.description: Located in the heart of Yogya, this is the city’s main street. Once was the ceremonial avenue for the Sultan. While steeped in history, today, Malioboro is the place to come to shop.

data.title: Parangtritis Beach
data.description: Located around 28 km (17 miles) from Yogya, Parangtritis is a mystical beach where dramatic jagged cliffs meet a glistening volcanic black sand beach.

data.title: The Kraton
data.description: The palace of Yogyakarta, known as the Keraton (also spelled kraton or karaton), is a grand complex that was meticulously planned to reflect the Javanese cosmos. Today, the Keraton is a piece of living history and tradition.

data.title: Kalasan Temple
data.description: Located on the southern main road between the cities of Yogyakarta and Solo, Kalasan Temple is considered as the oldest Buddhist temple in Central Java.

data.title: Ubud Monkey Forest
data.description: The Ubud Monkey Forest is a nature reserve and temple complex in Ubud, Bali. It houses approximately 340 monkeys which are known as long-tailed Macaques (Macaca fascicularis).

data.title: Kuta Beach
data.description: On the Kuta Beach beach, people enjoy parasailing, banana boat trips or swimming. Before sunset, crowds rush to the beach waiting to watch Kuta’s legendary sunsets.

data.title: Seminyak Restaurants
data.description: Over the past 10 years, Seminyak has developed a world-class dining scene. Seminyak is packed with some of Bali’s finest and most well-established restaurants, while several of its roads are recognized as must-visit dining destinations.

data.title: Seminyak Fashion Boutiques and Outlets
data.description: Amidst  the many restaurants and cafes, the  Seminyak's shopping scene comprising  exclusive fashion boutiques and lifestyle brand outlets.

data.title: Mount Rinjani
data.description: The mighty Rinjani mountain of Gunung Rinjani is a massive volcano which towers over the island of Lombok. A climb to the top is one of the most exhilarating experiences you can have in Indonesia.

data.title: Lake Kelimutu
data.description: Unlike the Blue Lake in Mt. Gambier, South Australia, that changes color from blue to cold steel grey within a predictable period, or Lake Yudamari in Mt. Nakadake, in Japan, that changes from blue-green to green,  the Kelimutu  lakes are unpredictable as to when and what color they will change into.

data.title: Um Island
data.description: Um Island is a unique getaway if you are staying for a couple of days in Sorong, gateway to Raja AmpatKnown as the habitat for bats and seagulls, Um Island sits right across the the Malaumkarta village in Makbon, a short distance away from Sorong in West Papua.

data.title: Wayag Island
data.description: Wayag Island is one of the islands within the Raja Ampat district  where you can find pristine beaches with unique Karst islands that look like mushrooms sprouting out from the sea.

data.title: Misool Island
data.description: Misool Island is a remote, tropical hideaway, one of four largest islands in the Raja Ampat archipelago, world renowned dive destination in the province of West Papua.

data.title: Waigeo Island
data.description: Waigeo Island offers diving, rock islands, scenic bays walled in by towering cliffs, a jungle interior offering good birdwatching, and the cheapest accommodation options in all of Raja Ampat.

data.title: Kofiau Island
data.description: Kofiau Island is the smaller and least visited amongst the major islands in Raja Ampat, the world’s coral diversity bull’s eye.

data.title: Sawinggrai Village
data.description: Sawinggrai village is located in the Meos Mansar district, Raja Ampat, West Papua province. It is among the most recognized village besides Arborek in the same district.

data.title: Arborek Tourism Village
data.description: Finding underwater beauty is not so difficult here, in Arborek.  Along the Arborek pier, divers can simply plunge into the water and instantly find a most intriguing illumination of the glittering of a gorgonian fan just below the surface.

data.title: Sauwandarek Tourism Village
data.description: Sauwandarek Tourism Village is part of Meos Mansar district. This village is famous for its beautiful corals. In addition, there is a salty lake locally called Telaga Yenauwyau, which is located behind the village.

data.title: Patimburak Old Mosque
data.description: Patimburak Old Mosque was built during the Portuguese colonial era i.e., in 1870 by Imam Abuhari Kilian. It has unique architecture as it is a combination of a church and mosque with the same square form.

data.title: The Grand Mosque of Baiturrahman
data.description: It is more than just a masterpiece of Islamic architecture in the nation, its survival from the tsunami is viewed by many residents as a direct intervention from the divine.

data.title: The Aceh Tsunami Museum
data.description: The design and architecture were created by M Ridwan Kamil, renowned architect who is currently Mayor of Bandung, capital city of West Java. The building layout also captures the epicenter of the disastrous earthquake and Tsunami.

data.title: Iboih Beach
data.description: The waters are so calm and crystal clear that it feels as if it is floating in the air. The beautiful and natural beaches at Iboih will surely change your perception of a boat coming in to dock at the pier.

data.title: Muara Takus Temple
data.description: These Buddhist remains pose an enigma to archaeologists as to the date that they were actually built, which estimated either in the 2nd, 4th 7th or 9th century.

data.title: Kampar River
data.description: Bono Tidal Bore by the estuary of the Kampar river in the Riau Province is drawing surfing communities from around the world to this amazing Indonesian pororoca.

data.title: Tesso Nilo National Park
data.description: Today the Park covers an area of 83,068 hectares, having grown twice as large from the former 38,576 hectares in 2004 when it was designated as a National Park.

data.title: Kerumutan Forest Reserve
data.description: The grand Kampar River runs along its border, lined with thick mangrove trees. The forest extends across two regencies, Pelalawan and Indragiri Hulu, in the Riau Province, in the central part of Sumatra.

data.title: Anambas Islands
data.description: The Anambas provide a panoramic view of blue seas and green islands dotted with azure lagoons. Here are excellent dive spots where divers will be amazed at the colorful underwater life. All of the islands in the Anambas have fine white beaches which glisten and become even more beautiful as the lagoons fill with aquamarine clear water.

data.title: Bintan Lagoon
data.description: Bintan Lagoon offers 470 luxurious suites and villas, two championship golf courses, a dedicated Convention Centre, an array of seasports and land-based activities for the whole family, a number of international restaurants, and its own ferry service from Singapore with terminal in its own grounds with on-site immigration clearance.

data.title: Pelawan Beach
data.description: Its beautiful beach and blue water make it the pride of those living in Tanjung Balai Karimun. This beach has white sands, big rocks, and mangrove forests in its surrounding areas. The nature of Pelawan Beach is still well-maintained as you could see from its clean sand.

data.title: Ria Bintan Golf
data.description: Set amidst pristine white beaches, clear emerald waters and lush tropical forests is the Ria Bintan Resort. The combined 36-hole championship golf course designed by Gary Player, comprises an 18-hole Ocean Course and an 18-hole Forest Course.

data.title: Asian Jazz Festival
data.description: Held annually on the shores of Harbor Bay during the month of September, the  ASEAN Jazz Festival is an arena where some of the finest jazz musicians from the ASEAN region and beyond convene, collaborate, and present some of the best musical performances to the audience.

data.title: Abang Island
data.description: This fascinating underwater wonder is a perfect spot for both diving and snorkeling. The most fascinating feature of Abang Island is the existence of Blue Coral which only lives in clear waters with excellent water quality.

data.title: Bingka Bakar
data.description: Bingka Bakar is said to have initially been a royal treat for Malay Sultans and was served only at special ceremonies or to honor distinguished guests. It is a typical sweet cake of the Malay ethnic group which is also familiar on the island of Sumatra and other Malay dominated regions.

data.title: Nagoya
data.description: Nagoya Super Block in Batam offers products in several modern shopping malls within one compound. The city walk area is located in the mall, but it is designed with wide spaces to look like a “mini city”. In this area, visitors can also enjoy live music.

data.title: Sawarna Beach
data.description: Located by a peaceful little village on the south coast of Java Island,  Sawarna Beach offers a host of natural wonders such asits rushing river, lush forest, rocky hills, caves, and more.

data.title: Tanjung Lesung
data.description: Situated only 3 to 4 hours drive from metropolitan Jakarta, Tanjung Lesung Resort offers luxurious beach resort atmosphere comparable to those in Bali or Lombok, but with relatively easier access from Jakarta.

data.title: Pulau Umang
data.description: Umang Island, situated in Banten province, is a small island perfect for your tropical getaway. Especially when you've done some business in Jakarta, since Umang Island is only 4,5 hours away from the bustling city.

data.title: Debus
data.description: Debus is the traditional martial art unique to Banten that is imbued with supernatural powers where the actors called Jawara stab themselves with sharp daggers or pierce their face with lances, and still emerge completely unscathed as if invulnerable.

data.title: Ujung Kulon National Park
data.description: Ujung Kulon National Park is one of the world’s most pristine natural ecosystem and Indonesia’s prime national park. It is the last sanctuary of the critically endangered Javan Rhinos (rhinoceros sundaicus)

data.title: Taman Safari
data.description: Taman Safari Indonesia or the Indonesian Safari Park is a conservation center as well as a modern zoological garden with various collections of flora and fauna. The place to enjoy the beauty of it‘s nature, but also interact directly or watch the animals wander around freely.

data.title: Kebun Raya Bogor
data.description: Located in Bogor city, this botanical garden is an ex situ conservation site, a research center for taxonomy and plant utilization.

data.title: Pangandaran Beach
data.description: Pangandaran is one of West Java’s best kept-secrets as far as international tourists are concerned. It offers uniquely black and white sand, calm waved beaches and spectacular sunsets.

data.title: Green Canyon
data.description: This little natural wonder is located at the Kertayasa Village with 3 meter wide bridge made up of soil above the twin cliffs on both river banks. This natural wonder is surely a spectacular scene that you will not find anywhere else.

data.title: Tangkuban Perahu
data.description: Tangkuban perahu is an active volcano, situated 30 km north of the city of Bandung. The huge crater is an astonishing view and you can walk around and explore. It is the only crater in Indonesia that you can drive up to its very rim.

data.title: Ciater
data.description: Ciater Hot-Springs Spa makes the most of nature's rich rehabilitative resources, by pampering its guests in tranquil surroundings, delivering professional care.

data.title: Kawah Putih
data.description: Located near the charming little market town of Ciwidey, approximately 50 Kilometers south of Bandung. The Crater Lake and its surroundings are dominated by a pale white color which radiates a rather hypnotizing ambience.

data.title: Tebing Keraton
data.description: Located in located the northern hills of Bandung, Tebing Keraton perfectly illustrates the majestic vista of north Bandung’s fascinating natural landscapes as ones stands on the cliff.

data.title: Saung Mang Udjo
data.description: Udjo’s House of Angklung is the one-stop cultural workshop that offers a complete experience around angklung, Indonesia’s traditional musical instrument made of bamboo.

data.title: Bandung Culinary
data.description: Many people visit Bandung. You'll be amazed with what Bandung has to offer. From various food sold on street vendors to haute cuisine, every visitor will be able to find something to their liking here, in Bandung.

data.title: Bandung Factory Outlet
data.description: Bandung offers a large number of factory outlets where Jakarta shoppers regularly flock to, to find the latest trendy apparel at reasonable prices. Many of these outlets are housed in beautiful colonial homes, for which Bandung was once famous.

data.title: Pasar Baru Trade Center
data.description: Initially called simply Pasar Baru (the New Market), it is actually the oldest operating marketplace in the city of Bandung built in 1884. Pasar Baru Trade Center offers Bandung’s finest products and the sensation of old fashioned shopping style which involves the interactive art of Bargaining.

data.title: Kasepuhan Palace
data.description: Standing on a total land area of 10 hectares, the Kasepuhan Keraton is the largest, the most impressive and best kept among the Cirebon palaces, where every niche carries its own historic significance. All royal families of Cirebon still live on until today, but all are now subjects of the Republic of Indonesia.

data.title: Triwindu Antique Market
data.description: Nestled in the center of the city of Solo lies a market unlike any other; a market possessing the ability to transport you through time, pulling you tens, or even hundreds of years into the past. Here you can bring your own antique items to exchange for a different piece that you admire.

data.title: Sam Poo Kong Temple
data.description: Unlike most temples, the building does not belong to any specific religion, but rather functions as a place of worship for people of various ethnicities and religious groups including Buddhists, Taoists and Muslims. It is the oldest of 5 temples included in the Sam Poo Kong complex which spans across 3.2 hectares.

data.title: The Cave of Virgin Mary
data.description: The GMKA is the third cave in this part of Java dedicated to Mother Mary, next to the Maria Cave at Sendangsono in Yogyakarta and the Maria Cave at Sriningsih in Klaten, Central Java. The Cave of Maria Kerep has undergone several renovations in order to include more complete facilities such as function rooms for meetings and spiritual retreats.

data.title: Lawang Sewu
data.description: Lawang Sewu in the Javanese language is translated to mean "a thousand doors". On October 14 1945, the building became the scene for the bloody "Battle of Semarang". Many were tortured and executed during this battle, from which the building obtained its name.

data.title: Alas Purwo National Park
data.description: According to the local legend, Alas Purwo was the site where the earth first emerged from the ocean. Many seeking spiritual enlightenment and mystics flock. The Park is considered to have the most natural tropical rainforests and one of is the oldest in Indonesia.

data.title: Plengkung Beach/G-Land
data.description: Considered 2nd best waves in the world after Hawaii, G-Land's waves is unique because they break after 1 to 2 Kms, rolling  from east to west with heights reaching 4 to 6 meters in about 5 minutes intervals. The vast swathe of white sandy beach is surrounded by pristine lush green tropical forests.

data.title: Grajagan Beach
data.description: The vast swathe of beachfront is carpeted with beautiful black sand and decorated with caves and hills. Here, you can buy freshly caught fish directly from the boats or why not try sail along with them and catch fish the traditional way.

data.title: Pulau Merah Beach
data.description: Pulau Merah Beach is so called since just some 100 meters to the side of the beach is a picturesque little hilly island called Pulau Merah. The color of the soil and sand are reddish, at one time some bright red rays shone from the small hilly Pulau Merah island onto the beach.

data.title: Tabuhan Island
data.description: Although quite a small island, Tabuhan has wide sandy beaches, fabulous underwater life and has been discovered to be ideal for kiteboarding. Its reefs that are habitat of diverse fantastic sea life make visitors to immediately pick up their diving gear and plunge into the clear waters.

data.title: Fort Rotterdam
data.description: Standing majestically at the western coast of Makassar, Fort Rotterdam is recognized as the city’s most iconic landmark.

data.title: Bantimurung Bulusaraung National Park
data.description: The Bantimurung National Park has a total area of approximately 43,750 hectares. The valleys of limestone hills and steep karts walls with tropical vegetation have made Bantimurung an ideal habitat for various rare and endemic species of butterflies, birds and insects.

data.title: Taka Bonerate National Park
data.description: Stretching south of the main island of Sulawesi in the Flores Sea, the Taka Bonerate National Park in the Selayar Regency is predominantly a rich marine park , but it is alsohabitat to a number of bird species from land birds, to coastal and sea birds that frolic on the many sand dunes.

data.title: Sa'dan River
data.description: The Sa’dan river is one of the longest rivers on the island of Sulawesi, flowing a distance of 182 km and measures 80 meters at its widest point. Rafting the entire Sa’dan river can take two days, passing picturesque swathes of green ricefields, quaint traditional villages, steep gorges and high rocky mountains.

data.title: Alas River
data.description: This area is especially popular among the young and adventurous. The sharp bends and many rapids are challenging to white-water rafters.

data.title: Air Manis Beach
data.description: Air Manis Beach is closely related to the legend of Malin Kundang in West Sumatra, character fabled to have been turned to stone.

data.title: The Harau Valley
data.description: Dozens of waterfalls tumble down from 80 to 300 meters height into the valley below, cut by the Batang Arau River. Its beautiful landscape make the Harau Valley the perfect holiday getaway.

data.title: Ngarai Sianok
data.description: Ngarai Sianok is arguably the most beautiful scenery among West Sumatra’s many scenic sites, to be enjoyed particularly at sunrise or sunset. Its panorama is particularly beautiful in the early morning light.

data.title: Musi River
data.description: This famous river is the longest in Sumatra at 750 kilometers long. Taking the Musi River tour is a must for visitors who wish to know the Palembang.

data.title: Sultan Mahmud Badaruddin II Museum
data.description: Not only rich in its collections, Museum Sultan Mahmud Badaruddin II itself is a historical legacy, as it is a monument of the golden age of the Palembang Sultanate.

data.title: Lake Kerinci
data.description: Surrounded by boundless stretches of bright, green rice paddies against a backdrop of gently sloping mountains, seemingly a shade of blue; lies a vast expanse of calm, clear waters, dotted sporadically by small fishing boats gliding along its surface.

data.title: Kayu Aro Tea Plantation
data.description: Looking for a tranquil spot to clear your mind and refresh your body amidst fresh mountain air, cool breeze and natural surroundings? Kayu Aro may be the ideal spot.

data.title: The Tin Museum of Indonesia
data.description: The museum is the only Tin Museum in Indonesia and Asia which today is under the management of the Indonesian state enterprise PT Tambang Timah.

data.title: Lengkuas Island
data.description: Lengkuas Island is blessed with a pristine beach, turquoise blue waters and distinct huge granite boulders, the icon of Belitung beaches, located north of Tanjung Binga Village in Belitung and offers idyllic landscape, lush palm trees and staggering boulders that are great fun to climb on or swim beneath.

data.title: Kiluan Bay
data.description: Kiluan Bay is a beautiful and tranquil spot where you can see the herds of wild dolphins diving freely beneath the crystal sea, coupled with sandy white beaches against a backdrop of a clear blue sky are key elements representing the unabridged of it's natural beauty.

data.title: Lembah Hijau
data.description: Lembah Hijau, or Green Valley, is an all-in-one center for education, recreation, fun and entertainment. Covering 30 hectares, Lembah Hijau includes a range of facilities, offering a wide variety of activities and entertainment for people of all ages.

data.title: Pantai Panjang
data.description: Pantai Panjang boasts a coastline of fine, white sands that stretches 7 kilometers. As the beach has no reefs, its width expands to 500 meters when the tide is low.

data.title: Suban Hot Spring
data.description: Suban hot spring is just below the hills of Bukit Kaba in the highlands of Bengkulu Province, it's a pool of rejuvenating warmth surrounded by the lush beauty of nature.

data.title: Bunaken
data.description: Bunaken is an island in the Bay of Manado with various strange and colourful marine life along it's sea bed. The place where you will encounter a real “mermaid”, and you can also get a glimpse of sea life.

data.title: Tomini Bay and Olele Beach
data.description: Most of diving site take you just a few minute from town, Diving in Gorontalo mean diving within the richness of biodiversity, health and unique coral and reefs. Dive below the equator and discover heaven in the waters of Tomini Bay and Olele Beach.

data.title: The Equatorial Monument
data.description: Twice a year, the shadowless sunlight occurs here, as the sun reaches its zenith on the Vernal Equinox and the Autumnal Equinox. These bi-annual events are comemorated here as visitors and locals enjoy a five-minute shadowless moment in the best ‘hot spot’ of Borneo.

data.title: Sebangau National Park
data.description: Perfect representation of the pristine tropical forests of Central Kalimantan. These tropical forests form an important part of the world’s environment, supplyig vital oxygen for the entire planet.

data.title: Tanjung Puting National Park
data.description: The incredible jungle surrounds make this an amazing place to visit if you’re after a truly outdoor adventure. It is an oasis of pure clean air, a clear night sky as well as a home to the orang utans.

data.title: Maratua Island
data.description: Maratua Island in the Derawan Archipelago off the north coast of East Kalimantan, is a large tropical island partially encircling a massive lagoon on one end and fringed with sheer rocky walls and coral reefs along the other end.

data.title: The Bekantan and Mangrove Conservation
data.description: The Bekantan and Mangrove Conservation Park is the home of a large family of proboscis monkeys, called Bekantan, which have a long nosed and large bellied, and often referred as the Arborial Old World monkeys.

data.title: Lakey Beach
data.description: This is the kind of place where you can join in a soccer game on the beach with the local boys in the afternoons, watch villagers fish in the tide pools at low tide, or try spear fishing when the tide comes in.

data.title: Komodo National Park
data.description: Komodo National Park is the home of The Komodo Dragon (Varanus komodoensis) with beautiful panoramic views of savannas, rain forests, white beaches, beautiful corals, and clean blue seas.

data.title: Lake Tolire
data.description: Tolire Lake is set in a crater at the foot of Mount Gamalama, on the island of Ternate, North Maluku Province. It is a brilliantly blue volcanic lake that surrounded with many legends.

data.title: Weda Bay
data.description: The little known underwater sea gardens of Weda Bay in Halmahera that offers divers amazing sights in these pristine aquamarine waters. Here are abundant fish life, from pygmy seahorses, tuna fish, dolphins, to napoleon wrasse and sharks, and numerous other species of underwater life.

data.title: Lake Sentani
data.description: The stillness of the water is most peaceful, evoking a peculiar wonder whether such a lake should indeed exist in paradise. The embracing Cyclops Mountains to the north and the lush vegetation as backdrop, securely protect the twenty four villages surrounding the lake.

data.title: Baliem Valley Festival
data.description: By attending the massive Baliem Valley Festival, visitors will have a rare chance to learn and experience firsthand the different traditions of each tribe participating in the Festival without having to make the difficult trek to their compounds deep in the hinterland of West Papua.

data.title: Sipiso-piso Waterfall
data.description: Set in the beautiful highlands of North Sumatra, the stunning Sipiso-piso waterfall is located on the North side of Lake Toba. This long but narrow waterfall drops 120 meters into an impressive gorge below.

data.title: Wakatobi National Marine Park
data.description: Due to its magnificent underwater life, Wakatobi is fast gaining worldwide attention for its quality dives that can be made by beginners to professionals. Located right in the heart of the Asia-Pacific Coral Triangle, in the province of South East Sulawesi, the Wakatobi Islands offer crystal clear pristine waters and a rich bio-diverse underwater life, a true paradise for Divers.

data.title: Mount Bromo
data.description: Located some 4 hours drive from Surabaya, the capital of East Java, Mount Bromo is a part of the Bromo Tengger Semeru National Park that covers a massive area of 800 square kilometres.

data.title: Mentawai Islands
data.description: Mentawai Island is ranked by serious surfers as a must visit destination. Take a trip into the wild with an adventure to the Mentawai islands!

data.title: Kadidiri Island
data.description: Kadidiri is a paradise for divers for its stunning underwater landscapes, rich coral reefs and exquisite marine life. The waters surrounding Kadidiri support over a thousand species of sea creatures, many of which are endangered and protected.

data.title: Dato Beach
data.description: A soft white sandy beach, crystal clear water, staggering cliffs, beautiful rock formations, and swaying palm trees; far from the spotlights of more popular destinations in other major islands, Dato Beach with all its splendor is truly a secluded hidden beauty.

data.title: Danau Biru (Blue Lake)
data.description: Danau Biru is surrounded by high rocky hills, along with the rows of trees, that together provide shelter from the scorching sun. The bright blue color of the lake will definitely tempt anyone  to just dive in and submerge oneself  in its refreshing  water.

data.title: Lake Sentarum National Park
data.description: The unique water condition and the annual cycle of rising and falling water levels dominate the ecosystem and exert a strong influence on the lives of its people, plants and animals.

data.title: Loksado
data.description: Loksado is an isolated piece of South Kalimantan’s paradise with lush landscape decorated with wonderful waterfalls, rushing rivers, and the enchanting culture of its indigenous people.

data.title: Pombo Island Atoll
data.description: It won’t take you much more than an hour to cover the single strip of deserted beach, rarely visited by man. Enjoy the sensation of the cool sea breeze through your hair, and the warm summer sun on your skin on an island that is almost your own.

data.title: Ngurbloat Beach
data.description: Although it may not yet be popular, Ngurbloat Beach and its enchanting splendor is sure on its way to become one of the prime destinations of Maluku. This swathe of white sand is also what makes this beach so exceptional.

data.title: Tau-Tau Statues
data.description: In the Torajan culture, Tau-tau is an effigy that represents the person who has passed away. Carved from wood or bamboo, Tau-tau statues are usually found near where the body of the deceased has been laid to rest.

data.title: Bakera Treatment
data.description: Handed down for generations, some of Indonesian authentic traditional spa treatments are still practiced until  today and have made their way into the modern spa and wellness scene alongside other popular methods around the world. One of the most unique is the Bakera treatment of the Minahasa ethnic group living around Manado, capital of  North Sulawesi.

data.title: Andrea Hirata’s Museum of Words
data.description: A museum named the  Andrea Hirata’s Museum of Words stands as an inspirational window for all, that it is possible to achieve our dreams despite many drawbacks, just as the novel  has taught us.

data.title: Wangi-Wangi Island
data.description: Wangi-wangi is one of the four main islands that make up the Wakatobi Archipelago off the coast of Southeast Sulawesi, and is the gateway to the Wakatobi Marine National Park. The Wangi-Wangi waters are a magnificent underwater paradise, rich in stunning coral reefs and an impressive variety of marine life to match.

data.title: Sangalaki Island
data.description: Unlike other diving locations, the management of Sangalaki Island strictly maintains the natural conservation of this island. It is situated between East Kalimantan and Sulawesi.

data.title: Melawai Beach
data.description: Beside enjoying the beach, visitors could also see loading and unloading activities at the port, watching ships moving in and out, and enjoying various types of foods and drinks at the beach.

data.title: Kaget Island
data.description: Although there is no official account as to  the origin of the name, it is believed that it may have derived from the startling sensation one gets when entering  the island and one is greeted by the boisterous sounds of hundreds of monkeys amidst the dense trees.

data.title: Kecak Dance
data.description: A visit to the dramatic island of Bali will not be complete without watching some of the most captivating traditional performances the island has to offer. Aside from Barong and Janger Dances, another dazzling performance you definitely don’t want to miss is the traditional Kecak Dance, one of Balinese artistic masterpieces in the form of a dance and musical drama.
